    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. I want to make sure they really understand the importance of it. Could you expand on that? Maybe add a section about how this doctrine is basically the most essential way the Constitution ensures that the government doesn't just trample over our basic human rights under the guise of following \"procedures.\"",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To put it plainly, substantive due process prevents the government from passing laws that might follow correct procedures but fundamentally violate core human dignity. This is its most essential function: it guards against the state using legal formality as a thin veil to strip citizens of basic liberties. Without it, the Constitution would only guarantee fair *processes*, not actual *freedom*. Therefore, it is the primary legal mechanism ensuring that procedural legality does not become an excuse for tyrannical rights violations.",
      "source": "target",
